data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync calls throw — no opt-in workaround exists.**

In EF Core 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into sync-over-async. **EF Core 11 removes that entirely.** Every synchronous I/O call (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) now **always throws** at runtime, regardless of configuration.

### Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ToList()` → `await ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `await FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `await CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `await SaveChangesAsync()`
- All callers up the chain must become `async`/`await` too

The Cosmos DB SDK is async-only, so Microsoft removed the sync-over-async bridge entirely to prevent deadlocks and perf issues. Tracked at [dotnet/efcore#37059](https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/37059).
